Hierachical Clustering

We will do a viewer-friendly example of hierarchical clustering (specifically using the average method). The data we are using involves different life expentancies for different countries. The variables include

  • m0 When men are first born, this is their life expentancy (years)
  • m25 When men are 25 years old, this is the expected number of years they have left to live
  • m50 When men are 50 years old, this is the expected number of years they have left to live
  • m75 When women are 75 years old, this is the expected number of years they have left to live
  • w0 When men are first born, this is their life expentancy (years)
  • w25 When women are 25 years old, this is the expected number of years they have left to live
  • w50 When women are 50 years old, this is the expected number of years they have left to live
  • w75 When men are 75 years old, this is the expected number of years they have left to live
head(life)

We will now look at the dendrogram for this dataset using the average method.

dis <- dist(life)
cc <- hclust(dis, method="average") 
plot(cc)

Below is code that plots the same dendrogram as above and also the plot of the first two principle components for the data. The color-coding is according to the different clusters. The second set of plots is the first and the third principle component plotted against each other.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
pc <- princomp(life)
ct <- cutree(cc,k=4)

plot(cc)
plot(pc$scores[,c(1,2)],type="n")
text(pc$scores[,c(1,2)],labels=rownames(life),col=ct)

plot(cc)
plot(pc$scores[,c(1,3)],type="n")
text(pc$scores[,c(1,3)],labels=rownames(life),col=ct)

K-Means Clustering

religion <- read.csv(file="rel.csv")
rownames(religion)=religion[,2]
religion <- religion[,3:19]
head(religion)

For simplicity, we will select only the major religions. With this being said, we will filter out the original religion dataset and keep Christian (non-Catholic), Catholic, Jewish, Muslim, and No Religion.

data <- religion[,c(1,2,3,4,5,7,16)]
head(data)

Now we will determine how many clusters to use for our k-means clustering.

stepFlexclust(data, k = 2:12, nrep = 20)

Although there is a level of ambiguity in the stepFlexclust() function, but according to the graph it appears that the plot appears to begin to “level out” after 5 clusters. Therefore we will select \(k=5\). Now we will find the specific cluster assignments that result in the lowest within cluster distance. Below the cluster assingments (for clusters 1-5) for each country is shown below.

clustrelbest = stepFlexclust(data,k=5,nrep=1000)
